title: Tutorial on Using the Rich Text Editor for Dr. Steve Hranilovic's Lab Homepage
content:
Welcome to the tutorial on using the rich text editor for creating content on Dr. Steve Hranilovic's lab homepage. This editor is equipped with a range of features to help you create visually appealing and professional content related to research on optical wireless systems. Below is a guide to using each feature, with a focus on the most exciting and useful functions.


Rich Text Editor Features

1. Code Blocks

To add a code block to your content, use the code block feature. This is particularly useful for sharing snippets of code or algorithms related to our research. When you hover over the code block, a copy button will appear in the top right corner. The editor supports automatic language detection for the following languages: HTML, CSS, C, C++, C#, Java, JavaScript, Python, MATLAB, SQL, and Go, but sometimes the detection might not be accurate (ha ha).

def optical_signal_processing(data):
            processed_data = preprocess(data)
            signal = modulate(processed_data)
            return signal

2. Blockquotes

Use blockquotes to highlight important quotes or information.

Optical wireless communication is a key technology for the future of wireless systems.

3. Videos

Include videos to provide visual demonstrations or recorded lectures.

4. Images

Enhance your content with images. You can upload diagrams, experimental setups, or any relevant photos.

5. Hyperlinks

Add hyperlinks to direct readers to additional resources or relevant research papers.

Visit Dr. Hranilovic's Profile Page

6. Bullet Points

Bullet points are great for listing items or key points.

  • Infrared communication
  • Visible light communication
  • Ultraviolet communication

7. Text Formatting

  • Bold: Highlight important terms or phrases by making them bold.
  • Italic: Use italics for emphasis or to denote titles.
  • Underline: Underline key points.
  • Strikethrough: Strikethrough text that is no longer relevant or for corrections.

8. Headers

Organize your content with headers. You can choose from various header sizes to structure your document.

Header 1

Header 2

Header 3

Header 4

Header 5

9. Fonts and Sizes

Customize the font and size of your text to suit your needs.

  • Use different fonts to match the style of your content.
  • Adjust the size for better readability or emphasis.

10. Color and Background

Change the color and background of your text to make it stand out.

  • Color: Use different colors to highlight specific sections.
  • Background: Add a background color to emphasize text blocks.

11. Lists and Indentation

Create ordered or unordered lists, and adjust the indentation to structure your content clearly.

  1. Optical wireless system components
  2. Key research milestones
  • Development of infrared prototypes
  • Performance optimization techniques

12. Text Direction and Alignment

Adjust the text direction for languages that require right-to-left (RTL) formatting and align your text as needed.

Align left

Center align |

Align right

13. Superscript and Subscript

Use superscript and subscript for mathematical notations or references.

  • Superscript: E = mc2
  • Subscript: H2O

14. Clean Format

Use the clean format button to remove all formatting and start fresh.

By utilizing these features, you can create comprehensive and engaging content for Dr. Steve Hranilovic's lab homepage. Explore each tool to enhance your articles, research summaries, and more.


Happy editing!
